The **technical direction and constraints** — high-level. Technology *families*, non-functional
engineering targets, and the posture (security, compliance, operability) that the planner must
build within. Each choice is tied to an SRS requirement and a reason.

> **Boundary, again.** This names the technology *family* and the *limits* (e.g., "a relational
> store with ACID guarantees", "p95 < 200 ms"). The [`planner`](../../../agents/planner.md) picks the
> *concrete* library/version within those limits and designs the implementation. Don't pin exact
> dependency versions or write code here.

## 1. Technology direction

| Area | Direction (family, not exact pick) | Why (traces to) | Constraint for the planner |
|------|------------------------------------|------------------|----------------------------|
| Language / runtime | <e.g. a memory-safe backend language> | NFR-2, team skills | <…> |
| Storage | <e.g. relational, ACID> | FR-5 (consistency), NFR-2 | <e.g. must support 1M-row import — NFR-4> |
| Compute / hosting | <e.g. containerized, single region v1> | BR constraints | <…> |
| Async / messaging | <e.g. needed? sync v1, queue later> | NFR-1 | <…> |

> A dependency added later is a decision (the [`gate-dep-install`](../../../docs/HOOKS.md) hook gates
> it at coding time). This document sets the *direction*; the planner records the concrete pick in
> `decisions.md` when it commits.

## 2. Non-functional engineering targets

The measurable targets the implementation must hit, lifted from `srs.md §4` and made concrete for
engineering.

| Target | Value + condition | Source |
|--------|-------------------|--------|
| Latency | <p95 < 200 ms at 500 rps on the reference instance> | NFR-1 |
| Throughput / scale | <e.g. 10k concurrent sessions; 1M-row import> | NFR-4 |
| Availability | <e.g. 99.9% monthly> | NFR-2 |
| Resource budget | <e.g. fits in <N> GB / <$N> per month at target load> | BR constraint |

